entry.title: cros_next: fixed shelf unittest failure
entry.content:
This cl fixed the failure of shelf manager unit test due to the

crash of the overview item shadow.



The crash is due to the small test window which is 1x370 which will

not appear in real case. The small size leads to a negative adjusted

shadow elevation and finally make the shadow layer smaller than its

nine patch layer's border.



The cl fixed the issue by setting a more meaningful size to test

window.



Test: ShelfLayoutManagerTest.VisibleInOverview

Bug: b:293400777

entry.title: ash: fix potential uaf in DemoSessionMetricsRecorder
entry.content:
This code uses base::ScopedObservation to observe a Window. It

may call Observe() multiple times, but it does not necessarily call

Reset() before calling Observe(). ScopedObservation assumes

Reset() is called before Observe() (it has a DCHECK). If Reset() is

not called before Observe(), then the existing observer is not removed

before adding the new one.



This patch adds a call to Reset() to ensure it is not already observing

a window.



Bug: 1462483

entry.title: ozone/wayland: Reliable asynchronous cursor image loading
entry.content:
This introduces a Linux-specific asynchronous wrapper for

`BitmapCursor`, known as `WaylandAsyncCursor` that is modeled after its

Ozone/X11 counterpart, `X11Cursor`, and make `WaylandCursorFactory`

return `WaylandAsyncCursor` objects that will be triggered when the

cursor theme finishes loading on the IO thread.



This change aims to make Wayland cursor image loading reliable in all

cases. Currently, if Chromium tries to load the cursor before

`wl_cursor_theme_load` returns in the IO thread, WaylandCursorFactory

will return a `nullptr`. This is what causes the symptoms reported in

https://crbug.com/1408443, as the cursor theme might not be loaded when

Chromium attempts to obtain a new cursor object for a differently scaled

display.



This also eliminates `WaylandCursorFactory::SetDeviceScaleFactor` and

replaces it the `scale` parameter on the new method overload

`CursorFactory::GetDefaultCursor(type, scale)`. This also allows the

Wayland Ozone platform to load the appropriate high resolution cursor

image on hiDPI systems, which used to work until

https://crrev.com/c/4583534 broke it by removing

`CursorFactory::SetDeviceScaleFactor`.



Additionally, this CL fixes and reenables the WaylandCursorFactoryTest.*

unit tests that were disabled in crbug.com/1357512.



Bug: 1408443, 1357512

entry.title: graphite: Multi-device synchronization implementation in D3DImageBacking
entry.content:
Implement synchronization across multiple devices Dawn/ANGLE/D3D11/D3D12

in D3DImageBacking. This CL makes the following changes:



1) ExternalImageDXGI is cached in DXGISharedHandleState to ensure that

we don't acquire the keyed mutex recursively if multiple shared

images alias the same shared handle. Also, add some validation logic

to BeginAccessDawn to disallow concurrent keyed mutex access.



2) Extend the fence synchronization code in D3DImageBacking to support

multiple devices. Also, factor out common functionality for getting

the list of pending wait fences and state tracking into helpers that

are used for both BeginAccessD3D11 and BeginAccessDawn.



3) Support the case where we don't have a shared handle e.g. mappable

textures created for shared memory compound backings used by software

decoded video frames and canvas capture. For BeginAccessDawn, when

Dawn is using using the same D3D11 device as the backing, avoid using

a shared handle and instead pass the texture directly.



Bug: 1464274, 1464548

entry.content:

is around 20-30 min, which is near the current importer timeout of 30

min. Bump up this timeout so that the importer does not prematurely

abandon unlucky CLs (e.g., crrev.com/c/4727817).

entry.title: bento_button: Fix crash for desk switch button tooltip
entry.content:
The crash occurs when the desk switch button tooltip appears during the

desk switch animation. The root cause is that we update the switch

buttons after the desk switch, which means the switch button may remain

visible for longer than expected.



To ensure that the switch buttons are valid throughout their lifetime,

the solution is to update them before the desk switch.
